2. Terraform lifecycle parameters?
A. In Terraform, lifecycle is a meta-argument inside a resource block that modifies how Terraform handles resource creation, replacement, and destruction. 
   It includes create_before_destroy for zero downtime, prevent_destroy for protecting critical resources, ignore_changes to prevent drift from external updates, 
   and replace_triggered_by to force recreation when dependencies change.

   depends_on controls dependency order, while lifecycle controls resource behavior during create, update, or destroy operations.
   
3. Terraform about ignore-change param?
A. ignore_changes is a lifecycle meta-argument in Terraform that instructs Terraform to ignore updates to specified resource attributes during plan and apply,
   typically used when external systems modify those attributes.

4. How to upgrade AKS cluster?
   Check Current Version:
   az aks show --resource-group <rg-name> --name <cluster-name> --query kubernetesVersion
   Check Available Upgrade Versions:
   az aks get-upgrades --resource-group <rg-name> --name <cluster-name> --output table
   Upgrade Control Plane + Node Pools (Standard Way):
   az aks upgrade \
  --resource-group <rg-name> \
  --name <cluster-name> \
  --kubernetes-version <target-version>
This upgrades:

Control plane

All node pools (if not specified separately)

You will be prompted to confirm.
Upgrade Node Pool Separately (Recommended in Production)

First upgrade control plane only:
   az aks upgrade \
  --resource-group <rg-name> \
  --name <cluster-name> \
  --kubernetes-version <target-version> \
  --control-plane-only
   Then upgrade node pool:
   az aks nodepool upgrade \
  --resource-group <rg-name> \
  --cluster-name <cluster-name> \
  --name <nodepool-name> \
  --kubernetes-version <target-version>
Verify Upgrade:
Verify Upgrade

5. what is kubectl command for to see node size?
   kubectl get nodes
   kubectl top nodes
   Example output:
   NAME        CPU(cores)   CPU%   MEMORY(bytes)   MEMORY%
   node-1      250m         6%     1024Mi          20%

   To check node size in Kubernetes, I use kubectl describe node to see CPU and memory capacity and allocatable resources. 
   For real-time usage, I use kubectl top nodes. In cloud environments like EKS or GKE, I also verify the instance 
   type via node labels or the cloud provider console

